Media queries in CSS are used to apply styles based on device characteristics, such as screen size. For mobile devices, common practices include:

Setting Viewport: Include a viewport meta tag in the HTML head for proper scaling. <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1">.
Defining Breakpoints: Create media queries for specific screen sizes. For example:

html

Copy code

@media screen and (max-width: 600px) {
  /* Styles for screens smaller than 600px */
}

A rule set in CSS consists of a selector and a declaration block. The selector targets HTML elements, and the declaration block contains one or more declarations that style the selected elements. Each declaration includes a property and a value, separated by a colon and enclosed in curly braces.
To implement a rule set:
Choose a Selector: Determine which HTML element(s) you want to style. For example, p for paragraphs.
Create Declaration Block: Define the CSS properties and their values. For example, color: blue; font-size: 16px;.
Combine Selector and Declaration Block: Place the declaration block within curly braces after the selector.
Example of a rule set:

css

Copy code

p {
  color: blue;
  font-size: 16px;
}

Grouping: Combining multiple selectors to apply the same styles to different elements. For example:

css

Copy code

h1, h2, h3 { font-family: Arial; } 
Applies the same font to h1, h2, and h3 elements.
Nesting: Used in CSS preprocessors like SASS, where you define styles for child elements inside the parent selector block. For example:

scss

Copy code

nav {
  ul {
    margin: 0;
    li { list-style-type: none; }
  }
}
